Aeolian Processes

Sediment transport by wind. Source: Steven, E. (2015)

  • Aeolian (or Eolian) processes refer to wind-driven geological activities.
  • Wind plays a key role in erosion, transport, and deposition of sediments.
  • Common in deserts, coastal areas, glacial outwash plains, and drylands.

Erosion by Wind

Desert pavement. Fine-grained material is removed by wind, leaving a concentration of larger particles that form desert pavement. Source: Steven, E. (2015)

Deflation

  • The removal of fine-grained particles, leaving a surface of coarser grains.
  • Forms desert pavements.

Abrasion

  • Sandblasting of rock surfaces by wind.
  • Creates polished, scratched, and sculpted surfaces.

Attrition

  • Windborne particles collide, wearing each other down.
  • Produces rounded grains.

Sediment Transport by Wind

The process of sediment transport. The deposited particles (of sand, silt, and clay size) are entrained in by one of the four processes (Creep, Lift, Saltation, and Impact transport). When a particle rolls or slides across the surface, it is called Creep (Roiling). Lift is when a particle rises off the surface due to the Bernoulli effect. If the flow is turbulent, larger particles are trajected by a process known as Saltation. Impact transport occurs when one particle strikes another causing the second one to move ahead. Source: Steven, E. (2015)

Suspension

  • Fine dust particles are lifted and carried long distances.

Saltation

  • Medium-sized grains bounce along the ground.

Creep

  • Larger particles roll or slide across the surface.

Impact Transport

  • Grains collide, dislodging other particles.

Erosional Landforms Formed by Wind

Desert Pavement

  • A surface of coarse particles left behind after deflation.

Rock Pedestal (Mushroom Rock)

  • Wind erodes the base more than the top, forming a mushroom shape.

Zeugen

  • Parallel ridges of alternating hard and soft rock eroded by wind.

Yardang

  • Narrow ridges sculpted by strong winds, aligned with prevailing wind direction.

Mesas and Buttes

  • Flat-topped highlands eroded over time; buttes are smaller remnants of mesas.

Inselberg

  • Isolated steep-sided rock hill that resists erosion.

Ventifacts

  • Rocks shaped and polished by wind-driven sand.

How Wind Deposits Sediments

  • Wind deposits sediments when its velocity decreases, causing particles to settle.
  • This occurs due to obstacles, changes in wind speed, or moisture content.
  • The deposited sediments form dunes, sand sheets, loess deposits, and dust layers.

Types of Wind Deposits

1. Sand Dunes

  • Definition: Mounds or ridges of sand formed by wind deposition.
  • Formation:
    • Wind slows down behind obstacles, causing sand to settle.
    • Sand accumulates and migrates over time.

2. Sand Sheets

  • Definition: Large, flat deposits of sand without significant dune formation.
  • Formation:
    • Occur in regions with low wind energy, where sand settles evenly.
    • Often found near dune fields.

3. Loess Deposits

  • Definition: Fine-grained windblown dust (silt and clay) accumulating over time.
  • Formation:
    • Wind transports silt and clay over long distances.
    • Dust settles when wind slows down.
    • Loess deposits contribute to fertile soils.
  • Examples:
    • Loess Plateau, China
    • Midwestern USA
    • Europe (Germany, Hungary, Ukraine)

4. Windblown Dust (Dust Storm Deposits)

  • Definition: Fine sediments carried high into the atmosphere and deposited far from their source.
  • Formation:
    • Strong winds lift silt and clay into suspension.
    • When wind speed drops, dust settles.
    • Can contribute to soil formation far from the original source.
  • Example: Sahara dust reaching the Amazon Rainforest, enriching its soil.

5. Volcanic Ash Deposits

  • Definition: Wind-transported volcanic ash after explosive eruptions.
  • Formation:
    • Ash is ejected into the atmosphere and carried by wind.
    • Settles over large areas, forming thick deposits.

Factors Controlling Wind Deposition

  1. Wind Speed â Faster winds transport particles farther; slower winds cause deposition.
  2. Particle Size â Larger grains settle quickly; finer dust and silt travel longer distances.
  3. Topography â Mountains, vegetation, and structures act as wind barriers.
  4. Moisture â Humidity makes dust particles stick together, aiding deposition.

Depositional Landforms Formed by Wind

Aeolian processes not only erode and transport materials but also lead to various depositional landforms when wind velocity decreases. These landforms vary in scale and complexity, from vast sand seas to microscopic dust deposits.

Depositional Landforms include: - Sand Seas (Ergs) - Sand Sheets - Ripples - Windblown Dust - Loess - Dust in Ocean Sediments - Volcanic Ash - Dunes and types: - Barchan - Dome - Barchanoid - Transverse - Seif - Parabolic - Longitudinal - Star - Reversing

Sand Seas (Ergs)

  • Definition: Vast regions of wind-blown sand, typically forming large dune fields.
  • Extent: Usually >100,000 kmÂ²; found between 20â40Â° latitude in dry, subsiding trade wind belts.
  • Features:
    • Composed of large dunes.
    • Found in deserts of North/South Africa, Asia, and Australia.
  • Examples: Rubâ al Khali (Saudi Arabia), Sahara Desert, Martian polar regions.

Sand Sheets

  • Definition: Flat or gently undulating plains of sand, formed by successive deposition of wind-blown materials.
  • Characteristics:
    • Lacks prominent dunes.
    • Often have a thin grass cover.
    • Deposits include sand from migrating ripples and wind-suspended dust.
  • Example: Selima Sand Sheet, Eastern Sahara.

Ripples

  • Definition: Small-scale, wavelike ridges formed by the saltation of sand grains.
  • Scale: Centimeters to meters in wavelength.
  • Formation:
    • Created by wind pushing grains in short jumps (saltation).
    • Typically aligned perpendicular to wind direction.

Windblown Dust

  • Composition: Fine-grained particles of silt and clay size.
  • Transport:
    • Can travel long distances in suspension.
    • Forms dust storms under strong winds.
  • Significance:
    • Adds fertility to soils.
    • Affects climate and visibility.

Loess

  • Definition: Thick accumulations of wind-deposited silt.
  • Composition: Primarily silt-sized particles, high porosity (~60%).
  • Origin: Often derived from glacial outwash plains.
  • Distribution:
    • China: Loess Plateau (Huangtu Plateau).
    • USA: Palouse region, Midwest, and Mississippi River Valley.

Dust in Ocean Sediments

  • Process: Fine particles carried by wind and deposited into oceans.
  • Significance:
    • Contributes to abyssal clay and pelagic sedimentation.
    • Reflects continental climatic conditions.

Volcanic Ash (Tephra)

  • Definition: Fine volcanic particles ejected during eruptions and transported by wind.
  • Behavior:
    • If erupted high enough, can be suspended for days or weeks.
    • Eventually settles as widespread deposits. -Impact:
    • Affects air travel, climate, and landscape development.

Dunes

Dunes are mounds or ridges of sand formed when wind velocity drops and sand is deposited. They are asymmetrical with a gentle windward slope and a steeper leeward slipface.

Factors Influencing Dune Shape

  • Sand supply
  • Wind speed and direction
  • Vegetation
  • Surface roughness

Types of Sand Dunes

Type Shape / Features Wind Conditions Sand Supply Typical Environment
Barchan Crescent-shaped with horns pointing downwind; single slipface Unidirectional Limited Desert floors
Dome Circular or elliptical mounds; no slipface Variable or light winds Limited Transition zones
Barchanoid Linked barchans forming wavy ridges Steady unidirectional Moderate to abundant Between barchans and transverse
Transverse Long ridges perpendicular to wind direction; single slipface Constant, moderate Abundant Sand-rich deserts
Seif Long, narrow, sinuous ridges parallel to prevailing wind Bidirectional or shifting Moderate Desert interiors
Parabolic U-shaped; horns point upwind; stabilized by vegetation Constant coastal winds Moderate to abundant Coastal or semi-arid with vegetation
Longitudinal Long, straight/sinuous ridges aligned with average wind direction; dual slipfaces Bidirectional or converging wind fronts Moderate Arid deserts
Star Star or pyramid shape with arms radiating from a central peak; multiple slipfaces Multidirectional Abundant Large dune fields
Reversing Hybrid between star and transverse; two slipfaces Alternating Variable Transitional environments

Major Types of Sand Dunes

Major types of sand dunes. aâb Barchan dunes form in areas that have a limited amount of sand, a nearly constant wind direction, and a generally flat, dry surface with little vegetation. The tips of barchan dunes point downwind. câd Transverse dunes form long ridges of sand that are perpendicular to the prevailing wind direction in areas of little or no vegetation and abundant sand. e Seif dunes (also called Longitudinal dunes) form long, parallel ridges of sand aligned roughly parallel to the prevailing wind direction. They typically form where sand supplies are limited. f Parabolic dunes typically form in coastal areas that have a partial cover of vegetation, a strong onshore wind, and abundant sand. Source: Steven, E. (2015)
